scientific.name: Histrionicus histrionicus
trip.comments: Penobscot Valley Audubon Chapter boat trip around Isle au Haut looking for Harlequin Ducks.  We navigated the south shore of Isle au Haut, and nearby islands, including: Black Horse, White Horse, Great Spoon.
species.comments: 210+: --along south shore of Isle au Haut: 120; --Black Horse Island: 20+, did not cover west side of island; --White Horse Island: 30+, did not cover west side of island; --Great Spoon Island: 30+, did not cover west side of island; --The Cowpen and York Island: 10+ birds.----Note: Little Spoon Island was not censused, nor eastern shore of Isle au Haut from south of Horseman Point, north.  Count of 210+ individuals highest by boat trip.  First time we have covered by boat Isle au Haut and surrounding islands.

trip.comments: From the birding journals of James R. Hill, III:  "3 August 1990.  Bar Harbor, Maine.  Exploring Acadia (bog and coastal areas).  Downy Woodpecker, Red-eyed Vireo, Gold-Crowned Kinglets, Red-breasted Nuthatch, Starling, Blue Jay, Herring Gulls, Common Yellowthroat, Chipping Sparrow, Ring-billed Gull, Black-capped Chickadee, Arctic Tern, Song Sparrow, Junco, Crow, Cormorant, Northern Flicker, Eider, Red-winged Blackbird, Semipalmated Plover, Barn Swallows, Semipalmated Sandpiper, Tree Swallows. Cliff Swallows, Sharp-shinned Hawk (attacking swallows!), Ruddy Turnstone, Wood Thrush, Kingfisher, Goldfinch, female Harrier, Peewee, Black Duck and babies, Mourning Dove, Black-throated Green Warbler, Hermit Thrush, Robin, Cedar Waxwing, Broad-wing Hawk, Chestnut-sided Warbler, Winter Wrens, countersinging in tall black spruce forest that smelled wonderful.  White-throat Sparrows, Least Flycatcher, and Red Squirrels."

trip.comments: Lorraine and Steve Walsh (Brooklyn NY)  THE SUMMER OF WHITE-WINGED CROSSBILLS  This was an amazing day when we came into the valley cove trail a women walked out saying "I don't know what it is but there is a cacophony of sound back there on the trail"   It turns out that there were 400 White-winged Crossbills in every spruce tree eating the seeds, dropping the cones and making a racket.... I have never seen so many birds in one place at one time!!  A real  irruptive flock and a life time experience.

trip.comments: Drove one-way road from end to end, w/ stops.  Walked 1 mile (? can't remember) trail to Schoodic Head and back.  Walked (and drove? can't remember) Schoodic Point area. ----The top of the hill was quiet.  Almost all of the bird activity was lower down.  Most songbird sightings all took place at the trailhead for the Alder Trail, which lies at the end of a dirt road that leads to a small park building.  This area lies just S of Schoodic Head.----Weather - Mostly cloudy, 24F.  Mostly sunny in afternoon, high 38F.  Variable breeze.  34F at 3:30.----Also - I presume that the heavy wingbeats of a flushed bird in the alder swamp there were a Ruffed Grouse based on habitat but I suppose it could have been a Spruce.  There is no option for "grouse sp." on this list.----Mammals - Red Squirrel, 10.  seal sp., 1.  porpoise (?) sp., 1.

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: This count was done while participating in the Acadia NP Peregrine Watch.  Two of us were the "leads" in this and during the 3 hours over 120 visitors joined us.  The Red-shouldered Hawks were clearly visible with banded tails and the wing "window."  One was attacked and chased by a PEFA, and was observed to be missing some primary feathers.  That particular individual was seen twice during the watch.  A second Red-shouldered Hawk was seen later flying with the three Broad-winged Hawks.  The Broad-winged Hawks seemed more unusual to me, as they were flying together from the direction of Bar Harbor and then circled together "kettling" up and over the cliff-face.  The Bald Eagle was an immature bird.

trip.comments: There were 2 Raptor rangers and a regular volunteer in addition to myself and a changing scene of visitors that added up to193 today. The weather was warm and mostly overcast with a few breaks of sun and a few spectacular fog falls over the cliff.
species.comments: The birds were usually visible every 10 or 15 minutes most of the morning. Usually only one at a time but sometimes both. They would fly to various perches that we were sometimes able to scope or sometimes they were hidden. Sometimes they flew out of the area either N or S as if they were hunting, but we never saw food. The last time we saw them they flew somewhat together over the mash east of us and soared a while and then flew out of sight.

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: We stopped to show some friends the peregrine nesting cliff and we were rewarded with a show from a flying peregrine.
species.comments: In general the bird was flying frequently to different perches, sometimes trees, sometimes ledges, and once a small nook between some rocks high on the right side of the cliff.   Specifically, it first was flying in the lower part and not seen much because of the foreground trees.  After about 10 or 15 minutes it started flying along the mid-face of the cliff and landed on various trees or rocks. It stayed for a few minutes on one smallish whitish square rock that was below the left-hand end of a long moss covered ledge. There I could see with the scope that it had a nearly white breast. Next it flew up over the cliff, but reappeared shortly and flew and dove and landed on the cliff top or the trees in quite a flight show. It once took a break from the show and squeezed into a small rook nook which may  be near the No. 13 arrowhead rock on the watch instructions. The flight show ended when it went back down below the level of the foreground trees. We waited another 15 minutes with no more sightings before we left.

species.comments: At times we could see all 3 juveniles and the 2 parents.  All the young are now out of the nest and practicing flying alone or by following each other or a parent. The parents still feed them on a cliff. one time late in the watch the parents saw an imm. eagle in the area and chased it across the face of the cliff and at the same time chased it down toward the water. trip.comments: This was our first day doing the Peregrine watch at Echo Lake because there is a pair with 3 young. We shared the watch with 37 other visitors. About half of them stayed more than 30 minutes in order to see the parent birds come in to feed the chicks. So It is a very different experience than at the precipice.
species.comments: 2 adults and 3 young. The young were banded a week ago when they were still mostly downy, but getting some feathers, Now they are almost completely feathered and practicing flapping their wings. They are all still at the nest site which was an old Raven's nest. The parents came in 3 times this morning with food.

trip.comments: Bruce Barker from Dixmont and I spent a little time along Ocean Drive from Sand Beach to Otter Cliffs.  The continuing story of ALCIDS  along the coastal edge of the Down East Coast was reiterated again  today with 5 Razorbills and many Black Guillemot found here this morning. Razorbills appeared to be all immature birds in various This January's SeaBC shed light on the shear numbers of Alcids, at least in the transects we ran from Northeast harbor to just south of Mount Desert Rock.--Black Scoter are still present in good numbers here as well as both Grebe and close to twenty Common Loon.  Purple Sandpiper were seen flying along the rock edge beyond Thunderhole. Bruce found 5 FOY on this trip.

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: The Bar Harbor Inn staff and myself spent a little time at the Preicpice Trail parkinglot looking for Peregrine Falcon. Success ... we had the male come to the cliff face above the nest site and an  aerial transfer of food took place with the female coming off the cliff to meet the male who came in from the north calling.
species.comments: The Bar Harbor Inn staff and myself spent a little time at the Preicpice Trail parkinglot looking for Peregrine Falcon. Success ... we had the male come to the cliff face above the nest site and an  aerial transfer of food took place with the female coming off the cliff to meet the male who came in from the north calling.   We put the birds in the scope but the female slipped behind a rock and we had to leave.

trip.comments: A group of people interested in a deeper understanding of coastal MDI.  Today we had an opportunity for everyone to see a Peregrine Falcon on Old Soaker. Comparing sizes of the Herring Gull it appeared to be a male adult. We had seen a flock of Sanderling, Least Sandpiper and a couple of Spotted,  so there were certainly Peregrine sized prey everywhere. What better place to observe that long rocky coast from Sand Beach to Otter Point.
species.comments: very clearly an adult bird sitting in the middle of Old Soaker. All 31 people took a look at this bird

common.name: Harlequin Duck
scientific.name: Histrionicus histrionicus
trip.comments: Barbara and I joined the Island Heritage Trust boat trip to see Harlequin Ducks around Isle au Haut.  This list includes birds seen from the Isle au Haut dock in the village south around Western Ear to Head Harbor and then back.  The waves were sufficient that we didn't go around Eastern Ear and the small islands to the east, an area that supports many more Harlequin Ducks.
species.comments: At least 87 individuals counted in separate flocks numbering from 2 to 18 individuals.  This is probably an under-estimate by perhaps 10%.  This number is similar to what I counted in the 1870s and early 1980s.----This flock of 15 Harlequins was right against the surf.----<iframe src="https://www.flickr.com/photos/103802626@N05/13513503883/player/" width="500" height="188" frameborder="0"></iframe>----<iframe src="https://www.flickr.com/photos/103802626@N05/13513754034/player/" width="500" height="204" frameborder="0"></iframe>

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: Weston Forsblad road up on a bike while I was scoping out Champlain Mountain for Peregrine Falcon. While we were standing there Weston was telling me about his experience at this same location yesterday when the male Peregrine came in with some food and an aerial food exchange took place right in my scope.  These are the first two Peregrine on the Island for me this year and well worth the wait on EARTH DAY 2014.
species.comments: Weston Forsblad road up on a bike while I was scoping out Champlain Mountain for Peregrine Falcon. While we were standing there Weston was telling me about his experience at this same location yesterday when the male Peregrine came in with some food at 8:27 and an aerial food exchange took place right in my scope.  These are the first two Peregrine on the Island for me this year and well worth the wait on EARTH DAY 2014.

trip.comments: SeaWatching at Seawal. 28F wind NW gusting to 20 mph, cold. High Tide with 6-9 foot waves. Heatwaves made it very difficult with the early light to see birds with detail offshore so I muddled along. The wind at times was howling offshore with crashing waves at any ledge. Good movement today despite the wind. Lo and over the waves many birds were moving on determined flights towards the east. Nothing stuck out today except the cold. Many birds were unidentifyable because of tall waves and windy conditions compounded by the tall chop.
species.comments: 2 birds were scoped as the flew west to east . Heavy body and large bill obious.

common.name: Peregrine Falcon

trip.comments: Cadillac Mountain Snowy Owl bike ride. Starting at the West Ridge trail at the south ridge trail I found an immature female sitting on an out crop about 500 plus feet below my position. I walk down the West Ridge working my way towards the Snowy. This white faced and V-neck bird allowed me to sit in a fix location for a long period of time. After about an hour it flew right at me on its way across the mountain.  Pretty good photos of this close encounter.
species.comments: One Peregrine  flew across West Ridge kind-of over the Snowy flying to the Northeast. Photos taken

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: Sea-watching at Seawall. Cloudy 39F, Wind 0-4 mph North, Low tide. One Red-throated loon scope well, Gannets and Loons on the move with several NOGA not migratory but foraging and seen moving northeast. One Peregrine Falcon seen moving along the shore than stopping and spending about 40 minutes on the peninsula off Wonderland  before disappearing. Most of the migratory activity at Seawall seemed to be far off shore at the limit of resolution for the scope. This put many of the un-identified birds out by the Ducks moving east to west.  Several of these flocks were large.

common.name: Short-eared Owl
scientific.name: Asio flammeus
trip.comments:
Summit, pond, south ridge.
Submitted from eBird for iOS, version 1.1.3 Build 30
species.comments: Big surprise. Flushed out of small wiregrass patch just north of summit. Close range. Distinctive face seen. Large owl, owl head shape and facial discs, rounded wings, brown-bufff colored above. Lighter tan patches (primary bases) on outer upper wings.  Distinctive floppy, indirect flight as the bird flew west over the ridge and then out of sight. Familiar with this bird from the midwest and occasional rarity in the northeast.

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
subspecies.common.name: Peregrine Falcon (North American)
subspecies.scientific.name: Falco peregrinus anatum
trip.comments: Had a hunch about Peregrine Falcon today and sure enough I located an adult screeching and displaying using single note, grunts and chortles which I had not heard before, almost eagle like. Seemed to be aggressively circling the valley and landing repetitively on the Valley Peak  cliffs. Only one bird was seen. There were no birds yesterday as we were on Valley Peak cliffs and across the cliff ridge overlooking Jordan Pond. Distant photos with a short lens.
species.comments: After talking to Bruce C  at ANP we are not sure if these birds are migratory, as one seemed to be at Jordan Cliffs. This bird seemed very focused on Valley Cove. Possibly a female just based on size. Seemingly aggressive behavior, flying around the valley screeching and emitting single note grunts or chortles when flying and sitting, almost bald eagle like calls. FOY for me. Checking with the park to see if there are new birds recorded yet.  They have been seeing a bird at the Precipice cliffs, Jordan Cliffs  which flew north and my bird today at Valley Cove. This bird was using Valley Peak cliffs landing on different precipices where it would sit quietly for some time than begin calling before leaping off with a few rapid wing beats before circling several times before landing again. Short stooping flights as it approached the next landing site.

A family with a little boy and girl stopped by and we invited the children to look through the scope. Both children saw a perched bird. Another falcon briefly came off cliff face to make a couple of small diameter circles in front of the cliff face very near the other adult bird which remained perched the entire time.
species.comments: both adults. one perched entire time on upper ledge at lower cliff face where there is a particle rectangular cut out in cliff face. Other bird made a few small diameter circles and then went back to perch on cliff but not in vicinity of first bird.

common.name: Grasshopper Sparrow
scientific.name: Ammodramus savannarum
locality: College of the Atlantic's Peggy Rockefeller Farm
trip.comments: Birds observed while visiting Peggy Rockefeller Farm.
species.comments: First identified by its distinctive, grasshopper-like, buzzy call coming from a fallow pasture. Eventually, it popped up to briefly sing again from the top of some grass. A smallish sparrow, clear, almost buffy breast; thin, white eye-ring; faint, dark, and thin lores trailing from the eye back; orangish-yellow supraloral; gray cheek; chestnut nape and shoulder; pale and thin crown stripe bordered by wider, darker stripes.

species.comments: One bird found initially by Greg Miller and seen by the entire crowd at the Precipice trailhead parking lot.  Reminded me of the old days during 93-95 when Acadia National Park when I would stand and talk to tourist for hours about the Precipice Perigrine's. After two seasons of Michael Good being at the trailhead, Acadia National Park began the Precipice education program, which has been a resounding success..

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: Kirsten and son Michael (11) had an opportunity of a life time when the 4 Peregrine chicks were visible  on the Precipice ledge they call their home. I have been watching these birds since 1993. Three different nest locations have been used including their current location since they first nested here in 1991.  Many amazing feats of flying have been observed here by 1000's of people. Bald Eagles have been chased away and once a Turkey Vulture was chased in a full dive down the face of the Precipice, where the female Peregrin landed on the TV's back and plucked out a feather.....which floated to the ground 150 feet away. --  In 1993 when I launched Down East Birdwatching and Nature Tours , I would spend hours watching and observing Peregrine Falcon,  a new species reintroduced into the world after decades of ignorance lead to their extirpation in 1963. In 1993,  People from around the world coming to Acadia National Park  would stop and talk to me about Peregrine life histories and the current amazing fact that these birds are returning to this cliff face to  raise young predators.  Here I am again this morning, after 24 years,  showing a young man and his mother  a bird species that was almost decimated by ecological ignorance, perpetuated by the money grabbers and the politically blind.  The second year I was out there, Acadia National Park began to send park rangers to the parking lot and so,  we all began talking about DDT and pesticides, raptors, fragile eggs and on and on.  From those early days  until today  there is an on-going Peregrine education program almost everyday............... and about 80 chicks later and 24 years.... I am once again here looking at Peregrines in a nest.    Thank you to everyone who worked on this project. Let's all be so thoughtful about the future.

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: PEREGRINE amazing pics and views
species.comments: Five of us are trapped on the trail by a scolding female Peregrine Falcon with at least 3 of the 4 first year birds from the Precipice Trail. I had seen them together diving and playing with each other the day before. These are the recently fledged Precipice birds. This eastern side of MDI has tall Pinus strobus and rock cliffs which are perfect places to hunt for food and protect the immature birds. It is because of the rugged outcroppings along this eastern coast of MDI that our Peregrine 's are doing so well. As we tried to walk down the trail to the van the adult female came toward us very aggressively and trapped us momentarily on the trail with an aggressive behavior I have not seen before for this species. Her aggressive approach and loud scolding was more Goshawk-like. When the adult started calling all 3 immature birds flew into a large White Pine which we passed by earlier and then initially found the birds. The trail is really the only way back to our van so we were stuck. At one point the adult bird flew close enough that we were forced to take cover behind a partial blow-down.  We waited in amazementbehind that tree for about 15 minutes when the female abruptly departed, I suspect, having assessed that we were not a threat. The photo of the immature Peregrine was taken during our first close encounter when we first arrived

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: Nearing high tide. Waves created spray on shore, but offshore a gentle deep swell. Gray overcast; mild temps (high 30s); light wind
species.comments: Found in scope as I scanned the sea and horizon from the right-hand cul-de-sac at Seawall Picnic Area. First noticed an unusual number of Common Ravens circling above Great Cranberry Island, and zoomed in to high power on the scope. Raven behavior caught my attention, in that they were circling above the trees and not flying directionally; reminiscent of how Herring Gulls all fly up in the presence of a Bald Eagle. As I scanned the CORA group, one bird emerged from the individuals that was a Peregrine Falcon. It was soaring amongst the Ravens and periodically stooped with rapid wingbeats on one individual, which was flying to evade the strike. Sort of a slow-motion dog fight. At one point the PEFA was underneath that same Raven and turned upside down, flipped back upright and evaded the raven. Mostly it was the falcon in pursuit of one apparent target individual. Observation lasted a total 3 - 4 minutes before the birds moved past the visible tree line. Fascinating and exciting.

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: MNHO Upload: Peregrine Falcon Survey, observations by S. Dunham
species.comments: We saw two adults but the seas and distance prevented definite ID of sex on either. One adult was first seen on the cliff, the other on a log. The adult on the cliff made several vocalizations during the first few minutes of the survey. The adult on the log flew off and landed in a tree after flying around. The adult on the cliff then flew to a spot on the cliffs sheltered by trees and made several calls there before flying out and joining the adult on the tree for what we believe was copulation and then returning to the cliff. This adult eventually flew off to the east. The adult on the tree flew down to the cliff area protected by the trees and was not seen again. I believe the nest is in that location but could not visually confirm.

trip.comments: Bill Wood This is a field trip organized by Acadia Natural History Center located at 39 Cottage Street, Bar Harbor searching for Schoodic specialty birds including the Monotypic Harlequin Duck. -- Referred to as the "CROWN JEWEL" of the diving ducks, we had one male Harlequin Duck observed at close range during a low tide with ample sunlight. HADU male is a small billed colorful sea duck who frequents the coastal waters. and is found consistently at this location during the winter and off the coast of Corea, Me. It is a diving bird foraging on invertebrates and a variety of other prey. This oddly shaped sea duck and one of the most colorful, has a large white spot in front of the eye, forming white crown stripes washed rufus red on the steel blue head and flanks. Spot and dash markings near the auriculars lead to distinct white slashes along the flank. The tail is wedge-shaped.
species.comments: Monotypic. Referred to as the  "CROWN JEWEL" of the diving ducks. We had one male observed at close range during a low tide with ample sunlight. trip.comments: This is a report from today’s zero-carbon birding bicycle adventure. All reports were delineated by Maine Winter Bird Atlas blocks. I pedaled from my Town Hill home to Ocean Drive in Acadia National Park and back. The weather was clear skies; winds were light and variable; temperature was mid-30s F.
species.comments: First alerted to the presence of a PEFA by its typical screech-like call. Got my binoculars on it as it flew south along the summit ridge of Dorr Mountain. A large falcon flying fast, wings coming to a point, dark gray upperparts, pale underparts.

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: FOY PEFA on the nest with the male bringing food.  Watched as the male brought food to the female...food exchange. Later I watched the female go back to the nest and the male hang around near the nest. Last years nest location is the same. Under the boulder above the light I shaped granite. The male preceded to sit on the very top of the cliff watching over the marsh and all below. The female was on the nest, came off for food and seen later going back into the nest location. I captured, very poorly, the food exchange. The pictures are terrible but the exchange was caught from DSC--8278 to DSC--8284, where the food was taken. I was on the ground and they were near the upper part of the cliff.

species.comments: Amy missed; I saw this tern fairly close to shore and though I was expecting Common Tern, this bird had paler gray upperparts and the primaries showed almost no black, except on the edge of the underside. common.name: Golden Eagle
scientific.name: Aquila chrysaetos
species.comments: Immature observed soaring off the summit of Sargent Mt., being closely monitored by a common raven. It was never all that close but the high contrast white base of the tail stood out right away, along with two distinct white patches on the undersides of the wings (opposed to the messy look young bald eagles have). The golden nape and proportionally smaller bill were really only observed from photos, but the other features were striking with binoculars.

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: Match time submitted under Maine Peregrine Program
species.comments: Back entering data into NestStory. 1108h Setup; 1110h 1 adult pefa (suspected female) spotted on the ledge of last years scrape, after aprox. 5 min flew and perched to right on top of tower then flew to right center cliff and perched for aprox. 5 min, flew to ledge 5-10 meters to the right of last years scrape carried a stick awkwardly landed and began preening. 1138h spotted 2nd adult (suspected male) perched to the left of the scrape in a dark shadowy spot. 1250h Bik departed the site both adults still perched on either side of last years scrape, suspect courtship and selection of same scrape, no bands seen but no good opportunities. 1350h suspected male flew to the right of the cliff face, past suspected female. 1355h female flies from ledge to another spot further down the cliff face, possibly grabbed something from a food cache, makes ?ee-chup? call. Flies out of view, both birds now out of view. 1420h 1 pefa flies back to cliff, at first settles near last year's scrape, then flies and settles far to the left and closer to treeline. 1430h end of survey. __________________________________________________________________________________________

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: Match time submitted under Maine Peregrine Program
species.comments: Chris and I ran out today to Ironbound and we saw a peregrine pair that appear to have a nest in a new location further east than the 2020 nest location. We had that hunch last year, but could not locate it. This year we think we have located the general area, but you cannot see the nest from the water. The only way to see nestlings would be to look from down from the cliff top. The pair is also comprised of an immature and a mature bird. We believe the female is the immature bird and the male is the mature bird.

common.name: Black Tern
scientific.name: Chlidonias niger
species.comments: Juvenile. Tern with dark gray wings and black helmet.  Possibly two but not seen together. These shots were taken as the  tide was coming in. The tern was just beyond the rocky area where the gulls hang out,  in front of the parking lot and slightly to the left.  The tern spent about 20 minutes fishing right on the edge of the mudflats near that rocky area.  It was pretty easy to identify as it was probably 150-200 feet away from us.  My wife took a lot of pictures, she has a canon R5 with a 500mm lens. In one shot you can see how close it came to someone out on the flats clamming.

common.name: Harlequin Duck
scientific.name: Histrionicus histrionicus
trip.comments: Cold/ windy start, eventually quite pleasant/ calm, clear. Drove the loop road with short stops at Frazer Point, West Pond/ Pond Island, Buck Cove, an hour on Schoodic Head, and a couple of hours around Schoodic Point. Several groups of 6-8 porpoises off the point, scattered Harbor Seals with at least a dozen just in Bucks cove, and a brief mink sighting in the rocks north of the point.
species.comments: A male and four females at first, then joined by two more males. Beautiful looks in and out of the water- lots of vigorous bathing and equally energetic preening. Eventually moved off slowly, following the shore towards Winterport.

trip.comments: Spent some time at the top of Champlain hoping to see the Peregrine family. 2 Fledglings were flying below the mountaintop on the ocean side. One, I believe an adult, was being attacked by a very aggressive group of crows. This didn’t stop it from putting on a nice arial show. The fledglings returned a bit later making a lot of chatter as they were swooping and diving!

common.name: Harlequin Duck
scientific.name: Histrionicus histrionicus
trip.comments: Schoodic Point Seawatch (NAD) for the Schoodic Institute. Car birding: Heavily overcast with rain, moderate at times. fairly dim observation conditions for the first hour and beyond. 8 miles vis decreasing consistently until <2 at the end, winds ENE/E 2-10mph, seas 3-5ft, temps decreasing 43-36F. The light was very difficult for a while, but eventually got alright, and the birds were moving in fairly good numbers as well.
species.comments: foraging at the point

common.name: Harlequin Duck

trip.comments: Schoodic Point Seawatch (NAD) for the Schoodic Institute. Storm conditions; heavily overcast with persistent driving rain, 1 mile vis, winds S 15-35 with gusts 40-60mph, seas 12-16ft, 55-56F. It was difficult to position my car in a way that prevented driving rain from the south inundating everything. Poor visibility prevented adequate coverage, but it’s evident a proper movement still didn’t occur. I hope to try to get out a bit later as the winds shift.

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: Winter auto loop survey.
species.comments: Saw twice. First, it was circling far overhead. Minutes later it glided in from the ocean and headed deeper into the peninsula. It flew only ~45 feet above my head on the second viewing. Incredibly clear view of its hooded face markings. Distinct falcon wing shape, but obviously larger than an American Kestrel or Merlin. Noticeable barring on wings and tail feathers, with a darker bar forming at the end of the tail feathers and tips of wings.

common.name: Peregrine Falcon
scientific.name: Falco peregrinus
trip.comments: 41° Mostly sunny early on then a mix of clouds and sun, S wind 10 kn. Very little snow at the top of the mountain, slick icy conditions on a significant part of the trail on the way up. The conditions of the trail have deteriorated- much more ice after the recent rain and deep freezing temperatures.
species.comments: Sizable Falcon with dark head and cheeks and a barred belly with grayish/bluish above.  Long pointy wings and long tail. Flew in at the top of the mountain near the Hadlock Brook trail head as we prepared for our descent.

common.name: Harlequin Duck
scientific.name: Histrionicus histrionicus
species.comments: There was a large group of Harlequins swimming in the water. Then some of them hopped up onto a seaweed covered rock. It was difficult to count how many males vs. females there were because they kept moving and the glare off the water made it hard to see. I did count at least 8 females. They were all clearly harlequins based on the bold feather pattern on the males and the white patch on the side of the females’ face. I could also hear their high pitched squeaks.
